# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-cow-at-my-table] It covers the conflict between animal rights advocates and the meat industry, and their respective attempts to influence consumers.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-cow-at-my-table] It was directed, shot, and edited by Jennifer Abbott, who spent five years travelling across Canada, the United States, Australia and New Zealand to interview representatives on all sides.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-cow-at-my-table] The film intercuts these interviews with images of farm animals and industrial farming operations.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-cow-at-my-table] It explores what is sometimes popularly called factory farming.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-cow-at-my-table] The filming of *A Cow at My Table* drew early criticism from the Canadian meat industry, with both the Ontario Chicken Marketing Board and the Dairy Farmers of Ontario publishing articles warning of Abbott's actions.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-cow-at-my-table] Music for the film was performed by Oh Susanna.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner obtained his M.D. from Yale Medical School in 1909 and received the Campbell Gold Medal for the highest rank on his examination and the Keese Prize for his thesis.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-fleshless-diet] In 1916, Buttner was described by the editor of the *Journal of the American Medical Association* as a "recognized representative in the literature of vegetarianism." He argued for vegetarianism from a scientific basis.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner practiced medicine in New Haven, Connecticut.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-fleshless-diet] He was a member of the New Haven County Medical Association.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner is best known for his vegetarian book *A Fleshless Diet*, published in 1910.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-fleshless-diet] It was widely reviewed in medical journals with a mixed response.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner argued that comparative anatomy and nutrition demonstrates that man is suited for a fleshless diet and that meat is dangerous and unnecessary.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-fleshless-diet] His recommended diet consisted of vegetables, eggs and milk.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner wrote that "It is not illogical for vegetarians to use milk and eggs, as these animal products are distinctly less toxic than meat and also less likely to be disease-laden.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-fleshless-diet] A review in the *American Physical Education Review*, praised the book for compiling useful dietetic research but commented that it failed to show scientific discretion in the selected material.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-fleshless-diet] A review in the *Journal of the American Medical Association* recommended the book as a reference work whether or not one accepts Buttner's conclusions.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-fleshless-diet] A review in *The Medical Standard*, noted that the book was a "piece of special pleading for the propaganda which it is designed to promote […] We may say this, however, for Dr.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Salt was active in a number of reform causes in the late 19th century, including prison reform, education, socialism, and animal protection.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He later founded the Humanitarian League in 1891.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] In *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays*, he argued that a vegetarian diet was humane, economical, and practicable, and challenged common objections to abstention from meat.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Across these essays, Salt defends vegetarianism on ethical, social, and economic grounds.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He argues against the killing of animals for food, disputes the view that meat is necessary for health, and links diet to wider questions of conduct and social reform.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Several essays also attack blood sports and reply to objections made by critics of vegetarianism, including Sir Henry Thompson.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Themes developed in *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays* appeared again in Salt's later writings, including *Animals' Rights: Considered in Relation to Social Progress* (1892).
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] At a social meeting organised by the London Vegetarian Society on 20 November 1931, Gandhi said that Salt's *A Plea for Vegetarianism* had shown him that vegetarianism was "a moral duty" and not only a matter of custom or personal vow.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Robert Morris (1703–1754) was an English writer on architecture.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] His published works include *Lectures on Architecture* (1734–36), *An Essay on Harmony* (1739), and *The Art of Architecture* (1742).
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also wrote poems, essays, and pamphlets, and worked as a surveyor.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] According to Adams, Morris encountered *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood* in 1745.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Expecting an argument against flesh-eating, he instead found a defence of meat consumption based on a post-Flood reading of Genesis.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris disagreed with that interpretation and wrote a reply, which was published in 1746 as *A Reasonable Plea for the Animal Creation*.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] The treatise is made up of a preface, a letter to General Foliot, nine letters addressed to a friend, and a concluding reply to *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood*.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams writes that the central part of the book consists of letters Morris had written in 1737 and 1738 and later incorporated into the printed work.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris argues that humans have no natural right to kill animals for food.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He appeals both to Genesis and to "the nature and reason of things", maintaining that the food originally given to humans was the produce of the earth.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He rejects attempts to justify meat-eating through scripture, custom, bodily necessity, or animal predation.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also argues that humans are not naturally fitted for carnivory, and describes butchery and cookery as artificial practices rather than natural ones.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Drawing on writers such as Pythagoras and Plutarch, he attributes feeling and a degree of rationality to animals and treats their destruction for food as a matter of cruelty and injustice.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In her introduction to the 2005 republication, Carol J.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams describes the treatise as a neglected contribution to 18th-century vegetarian and animal-ethical writing.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She argues that Morris' case against flesh-eating is centred less on health than on moral obligation, and that his appeal to the "light of Nature" gives the work a distinctive place among early vegetarian texts.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams also comments on the book's epistolary form, noting that its letters are addressed to a flesh-eating friend.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She treats that structure as part of the book's argument, since Morris repeatedly answers objections and defends vegetarianism against the assumptions of a meat-eating society.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She further notes Morris' rejection of claims of human superiority and his attribution of sentience and reason to animals.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] On Adams' reading, these features connect the treatise to later debates in animal ethics.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Before its republication in 2005, the treatise had appeared only occasionally in modern writing.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Whisker, John Simons, and Rod Preece each referred to it as an early contribution to vegetarian and animal-ethical thought.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Simons described Morris, together with John Hildrop, as a precursor to Humphry Primatt.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Preece quoted from the treatise and placed Morris among earlier writers who argued for vegetarianism on ethical grounds, including John Oswald, George Nicholson, Joseph Ritson, and John Frank Newton.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In 2005, the treatise was republished in *Organization & Environment* with an introductory article by Carol J.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-sacred-duty] The film opens with footage of a NASA rocket launch, an animation of the Solar System, and a quote from Deuteronomy 30:19 about choosing between life and death (illustrated with images of Earth as seen from space, contrasted with an exploding atom bomb).
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-sacred-duty] This is followed by a statement that humanity has not been caring for the planet properly according to Jewish teachings, which precedes a section about ancient Jewish texts and sacred words that provide "specific instructions on how to be custodians of the world in which we live".
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-sacred-duty] Throughout the film, quotes from the Torah are contrasted with the various environmental threats facing humanity today; the quotes are also illustrated with close-ups of Hebrew scrolls, Jews praying, and scenes of nature.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-sacred-duty] The Earth is again seen from space and the camera moves in to focus on Israel, which the narrator cites as a microcosm of current global problems related to air and water pollution, overpopulation, climate change, and health concerns.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-sacred-duty] The film moves on to look at global problems, with scenes shot all over the world.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-sacred-duty] The focus then shifts to the United States, where all the relevant issues are discussed in detail.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-sacred-duty] Reference is made to *Livestock's Long Shadow*, a 2006 report by the Food and Agriculture Organization which claimed that livestock agriculture produces more greenhouse gases than all of the world's vehicles combined.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-sacred-duty] Next comes a brief presentation, illustrated with simple animated charts, on how meat production is an inefficient way to produce food for a hungry world.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-sacred-duty] This moves into footage of animal abuse on feedlots and in factory farms, and the pollution produced by these facilities.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-sacred-duty] The film then focuses on the advantages of vegetarianism for reducing pollution and solving world hunger.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-sacred-duty] With a change of diet toward vegetarianism, the film asserts that many of these environmental and health problems can be solved.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-sacred-duty] After some fast-moving images of people and nature accompanied by music, the film ends with the same statement from Deuteronomy about "life and death" being narrated over a shot of a sunrise.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-sacred-duty] The idea for the film was inspired by the writings of Richard H.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-sacred-duty] Schwartz (*Judaism and Vegetarianism*, *Judaism and Global Survival*, etc.) who also served as associate producer.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-sacred-duty] Schwartz had seen the Christian Vegetarian Association's 2006 film, *Honoring God's Creation*, and felt that a similar film would be effective in the Jewish community.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-sacred-duty] At the time, he envisioned the film to be about 30 minutes long, though the final film ended up being 60 minutes long.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-sacred-duty] Production began in 2005 with a basic proposal and outline in the JVNA's newsletter, along with a statement that Lionel Friedberg was willing to make the film for "a very low fee, basically to cover his costs".
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-sacred-duty] The film was funded by the JVNA through private contributions.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-sacred-duty] Preliminary drafts of the script were circulated among members of the JVNA advisory committee and others for input, after which the script went through numerous revisions.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-sacred-duty] Meanwhile, Schwartz and Friedberg set about interviewing possible participants and filming footage of nature in both Israel and the United States.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-sacred-duty] The showing of slaughterhouse footage was controversial, with some members of a test audience in Staten Island seeing it as propaganda.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-sacred-duty] Friedberg recalled, "Richard and I were accused of making a propaganda film for the vegetarian movement.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-sacred-duty] We were accused of showing 'horrors that are impossible to watch'." However, he maintained that the graphic footage was necessary.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-sacred-duty] In October and November 2007, *A Sacred Duty* was released direct-to-video and on DVD, with public showings in both Israel and the United States.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-sacred-duty] Over 35,000 copies were distributed free of charge to synagogues, educational institutions, and individuals, complete with permission to show the film without having to pay the filmmakers any royalties.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-sacred-duty] In addition, permission was granted to the public to duplicate and distribute the film free of charge.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-sacred-duty] Numerous short excerpts from the film were edited and re-posted by various YouTube users, and the full version became available on YouTube in January 2008.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Francis Hutcheson (1694–1746) was a philosopher of the Scottish Enlightenment and professor of moral philosophy at the University of Glasgow.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He was a leading defender of moral sense theory, according to which moral judgement arises from an innate sense rather than from reason alone.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He began work on *A System of Moral Philosophy* in 1738 and continued revising it until his death.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] In *A System of Moral Philosophy*, Hutcheson sets out a broad account of ethics, natural law, private rights, and political society.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The first book concerns human nature and the supreme good.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson discusses the faculties of the mind, the affections, and the will, and restates his view that human beings possess a moral sense by which they approve virtue and disapprove vice.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He argues that virtue is grounded in benevolence directed by reason, and relates moral life to providence and natural religion.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The second book deals with natural law and private rights.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson discusses obligation, contracts, property, promises, oaths, and legal duties.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He distinguishes between perfect and imperfect rights, and treats justice as distinct from broader duties of benevolence.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He also argues that laws should answer to reason, public good, and natural equity.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The third book turns to civil society and government.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson examines the basis of political authority, the forms of government, and topics including marriage, family, slavery, taxation, magistracy, war, and civil law.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He holds that political power must be exercised for the common good and with the consent of the governed.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Modern commentators have drawn attention to Hutcheson's discussion of animals in the *System*.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] In a 2007 article, Aaron Garrett argued that Hutcheson offered an early argument for animal rights by grounding moral consideration in sentience and the capacity to suffer rather than in rational agency alone.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Garrett also compared Hutcheson's treatment of animals with his discussion of infants, and placed him in a line of thought distinct from Lockean rights theory.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Michael Bradie likewise noted that Hutcheson treated cruelty to animals as morally wrong because animals are capable of suffering.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] At the same time, Bradie argued that Hutcheson retained a hierarchical account in which human beings, because of their superior rational capacities, may use animals when necessary.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Bradie described this position as an early attempt to balance human interests with concern for animal suffering.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Foulis in Glasgow and distributed in London by A.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] It appeared in two volumes in 1755, five years after Hutcheson's death; it was published posthumously by his son Francis Hutcheson the younger, from the original manuscript.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] A new edition was published in 2000 by Thoemmes, with an introduction by Daniel Carey, and was later republished by A & C Black in 2006.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] A further edition was issued by Cambridge University Press in 2015.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] It is a foundational essay advocating for vegetarianism, maintaining that a plant-based diet is essential for bodily health, moral virtue, and social justice.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley argued that meat consumption is unnatural, a "slow but certain poison", causing disease, which "pollutes" the body, and leads to vice and depravity.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] He prescribes the return to a "natural" vegetable diet.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] This work is regarded as one of the earliest and most fervent defenses of vegetarianism in English literature.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley wrote four essays on the subject of vegetarianism, "A Vindication of Natural Diet" (1813), the note in *Queen Mab*, in a section of "A Refutation of Deism" (1814), and "On the Vegetable System of Diet", which was published posthumously in 1929.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley first experimented with a vegetarian diet while at the University of Oxford according to Thomas Jefferson Hogg.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley began a vegetarian diet on 1 March 1812 along with his first wife Harriet Westbrook.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley began composing the essay in October–November 1812.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley met John Frank Newton during 1812-1813 and influenced his views on vegetarianism.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Historian Keith Thomas has noted that Newton's *Return to Nature* "provided much of the basis" for Shelley's *A Vindication of Natural Diet*.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The work has been republished since 1813, beginning with an abridged version which was published in Boston by March, Capen, and Lyon in an American collection *Vegetable Diet: As Sanctioned by Medical Men, and by Experience in All Ages*, edited by William A.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The essay was reprinted in 1884 in a new edition in London by Frederick Pitman and by John Heywood and the Vegetarian Society in Manchester.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The original title page was reproduced: *A Vindication of Natural Diet.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Being One in a Series of Notes to Queen Mab (A Philosophical Poem).* London: Printed for J.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The new edition featured a preface by Henry Stephens Salt and William Axon.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] In 1904, the work was republished in London by C.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Daniel as *A Vindication of Natural Diet and Extracts from the Works of Dr.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley used the imagery of slaughtering a lamb.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] In the novel *Frankenstein; or, The Modern Prometheus* (1818), which he is acknowledged to have contributed to, the Being is portrayed as a vegetarian.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The Being explained his vegetarian diet to Victor Frankenstein: "My food is not that of man.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] I do not destroy the lamb and the kid to glut my appetite; acorns and berries afford me sufficient nourishment." Shelley's views on vegetarianism are routinely incorrectly attributed to his wife.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] In *Laon and Cythna*, republished as *The Revolt of Islam* (1817), Fifth Canto, the Festival of nations held after the Revolution is a banquet where no meat is served.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The feast is vegetarian: "Never again may blood of bird or beast/ Stain with its venomous stream a human feast".
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] This is "The banquet of the free" where the guests are described as "reclining as they ate, of Liberty,/ And Hope, and Justice".
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The festival was not polluted by gore, "But piled on high, an overflowing store/ Of pomegranates, and citrons, fairest fruit,/ Melons, and dates, and figs, and many a root".
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley argued that eating meat was unnatural.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] He maintained that diseases and immorality arose from mankind's "unnatural habits of life".
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] A meatless diet was the best regimen for maintaining a healthy and disease-free lifestyle.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] He wrote that human diseases could be decreased by a return to a natural vegetable diet.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley argued that eating meat was a practice that polluted the body with syphilis and resulted in other ailments.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] In *A Vindication of Natural Diet* he wrote, "Should ever a physician be born with the genius of Locke, I am persuaded that he might trace all bodily and mental derangements to our unnatural habits," these unnatural habits being the consumption of meat.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] He cited the allegory of Prometheus who stole fire from the gods which enabled mankind to cook meat, thereby screening the disgust and horror of dead flesh.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] He concluded that a person with compassion and empathy for animals, "rising from a meal of roots", would be able to maintain a healthy and balanced diet and lifestyle.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley presented examples of how a vegetarian diet resulted in longevity and an increased lifespan.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The only threat of death will be that of natural, old age, that "old age would be our last and our only malady".
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The two rules he prescribes for a natural diet are to never eat anything that was alive and to drink only distilled water.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/abandoned-pets] Animal welfare laws in many states of the United States make it a crime to abandon a pet.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/abandoned-pets] Often, when abandoned, pets are forced to fend for themselves and become stray or feral.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/abandoned-pets] Feral cats are said to outnumber feral dogs and can become challenging to handle and socialize enough to be re-introduced to a new human owner.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/abandoned-pets] In general, only some newly abandoned cats and very young feral kittens can be tamed.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/abandoned-pets] There is a necessity to investigate interventions to prevent companion-animal relinquishment.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/abandoned-pets] Stray animals increase potential exposure to zoonotic diseases like rabies.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/abandoned-pets] Cat bites or scratches involving stray or feral animals are eight times more common than dog bites.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/abandoned-pets] The impacts of dog and cat predation on wildlife can also be significant.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/abandoned-pets] Some pets relinquished to an animal shelter will be euthanized due to a lack of space or financial resources.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/abandoned-pets] Millions of companion animals enter animal shelters every year in the United States.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/abandoned-pets] However, the number of dogs and cats euthanized in US shelters declined from approximately 2.6 million in 2011 to 1.5 million in 2018.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/abandoned-pets] This decline can be partially explained by an increase in the percentage of animals adopted, and an increase in the number of stray animals successfully returned to their owners.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/abandoned-pets] Studies show that the majority of people who relinquish an animal also report being emotionally attached to the animal.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/abandoned-pets] It has been reported that when forced to abandon their animals in an evacuation, people suffer mental issues such as grief, depression, and post-traumatic stress disorder.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/abandoned-pets] Recognizing the importance of pets to their owners and their role in public health is an essential first step in improving a public health problem that has been seen repeatedly in the past and is unlikely to change in the future.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/abandoned-pets] Pet abandonment increased during the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation/abandoned-pets] In early 2009, the ASPCA published advice for people facing foreclosure and the loss of their pets, recommending finding a foster or adoption situation for your pet, being aware of rental property rules for pets, and checking with animal shelters and animal rescue groups.
